  "prompt": "Why does lodha panel interfere in BCCI?",
  "response": "The Lodha Panel, officially known as the Justice R.M. Lodha Committee, was formed by the Supreme Court of India in 2015 to recommend reforms in the Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) after several corruption and match-fixing scandals. The panel was headed by former Chief Justice of India, Justice R.M. Lodha.\n\nThe key recommendations of the Lodha Panel included:\n\n1. Implementing strict age and tenure limits for BCCI officials\n2. Removing politicians and government officials from administrative roles\n3. Restricting BCCI office-bearers to one term\n4. Ensuring proper transparency and accountability in cricket administration\n5. Separating the roles of administrators and selectors\n\nThe panel's recommendations were aimed at bringing structural reforms to the BCCI and making its functioning more transparent and professional. The Supreme Court largely accepted these recommendations and directed the BCCI to implement them.\n\nThe panel's interference was essentially a judicial intervention to address systemic issues in Indian cricket administration and ensure good governance within the BCCI. While some saw it as necessary reforms, others viewed it as excessive judicial overreach into sports administration.",
